UP data for meta-analysis stats

Raissa Mendonca

18 Apr 2018

Last update on 10 Jul 2018

UP data using low-binding and high-binding sediments in Big Pup Creek and Salmon Trout to measure:

  1. Biofilm colozination on NDS cups amended with Cu and Ni at different concentrations. NPP, chla, and metal bioaccumulation measured after 4 weeks
  2. Benthic invertebrate colonization on trays with the same metal amendments for 28 days. Inverts identified to family.
  3. Cotton strip decomposition

1. Net primary production

Log-linear models for NPP and sediment metal concentrations for low-binding and high-binding sediments

# Function to return selected summaries for an rma model and plots for
# rma.uni objects
rma.sum <- function(model) {
    sumList <- list(summary.rma(model), round(coef.summary.rma(summary.rma(model)), 
        4), anova.rma(model), round(weights(model), 3))
    names(sumList) <- c("summary.rma", "coef.summary", "anova.rma", "weights")
    print(sumList)
    if (class(model)[1] == "rma.uni") {
        plot.rma.uni(model)
    }
}

# Function 'rma.uni' used to fit fixed- and mixed-effects models via linear
# models in metafor Random effects in 'rma.uni' refers to the variance
# (tau^2) of the true effects/outcomes in a population of studies sampled
# from a larger collection of studies, assuming the population is a random
# sample of the larger collection In mixed-effects (moderators included),
# tau^2 denotes teh amount of residual heterogeneity in the true
# effects/outcomes, which is the amount of variation not accounted for by
# the moderators included in the model

fixedboot <- rma.uni(yi = R2.dif, sei = SE.boot.pooled, data = R2.sum, method = "FE")
rma.sum(fixedboot)

# Can't get the $weights to equal wi=1/se (fixed) or wi=1/se+tau^2 (random)
# using se or se^2
Calculating weighted linear regressions with lme() based on solution found on Stats Exchange
mock.lme <- lme(R2dif ~ Fixed, data = mock, random = ~1 | Study, weights = ~I(1/R2dif_SE))
summary(mock.lme)
